- computing bound (small), moderate (medium), and memory-limit bound (large)
No fine-tuning: using 1/4 of ranks for concurrency and same number of BLOB files.
- 4 is the same as the default Lustre striping.
A column consists a few to thousands of BLOB files;
Random access is available for both MPI and non MPI applications
During random access, BLOB files are opened on demand:
- Avoids overflowing file handle limits of the operating system;
- Writing requires a correctly implemented POSIX non-overlapping;
(Good because simulation data is nearly immutable)

We developed the bigfile library for storing data from cosmology simulations from HPC systems and beyond.
The library provides interfaces to store and retrive snapshots of BlueTides simulations run on NCSA BlueWater.
Each BlueTides snapshot contains 50 TB of table-like data for particle positions, velocities and more.
We present the library here to share it with the super-computing community.
We welcome new users, comments, contributions, and inputs that may lead to future enhancements to the library.
- Saving simulation snapshots to filesystem efficiently from a paralell MPI based application;
- Providing easy access to saved data from a variety of software platforms, esp from Python;
The performance of the library was evaluated and improved through the NCSA PAID program. We find that it
- achieves the I/O bandwidth limit of the file system;
- requires little tuning for good performance;
The bigfile I/O solution is very simple, and it can be generalized for any parallel and large table-like data sets.
The bigfile library is fully open source, hosted at https://github.com/rainwoodman/bigfile.
- core library consists of a few thousand lines of C code;
- bundled into a large application or compiled as a library;
- moderately covered by unit tests and coverity;
bigfile : efficient and effective I/O of large and simple data
- On disk, C-contiguous, tight packed binary representation of data
- Evenly spliced into many physical files (avoid FS tuning)
- For large MPI jobs, a reasonable number will give good performance -- e.g. 1 per 4 ranks
- Number of BLOB Files and number of entries per file
- DTYPE, vector size (NMEMB) and HEX encoding of binary data, followed by readable value
- Strided dense array like FORTRAN / numpy: base pointer, strides, size, and dtype
- only requires a functional file system for later data retrieval;
- reverse engineering the format is quick and fun;
- data is available even if bigfile is gone;
Data model of bigfile will look familiar because it is a subset of the data model of HDF5
However, the design of the data model of bigfile takes a different approach
- the HDF model is based on abstraction and representations of data ;
parallel IO came as an after-thought (HDF-MPI).
- the bigfile model is based on parallel IO from MPI applications;
a transparent container format is chosen to ease accessing data from a variety of software platforms
bigfile bridges the gap between MPI and non MPI applications;
- data production: MPI applications, parallel file systems, wallclock sensitive;
- data consumption: less wallclock sensitive; random access is important;
- data management : even less walllock sensitive;fine grain control is useful (e.g. partial data release)
- borrowed From numpy's data type descriptor
